WEBVTT

00:20.600 --> 00:21.720
CHAPTER XX.

00:23.340 --> 00:25.180
I sat one evening in my laboratory.

00:25.780 --> 00:29.120
The sun had set and the moon was just rising from the sea.

00:29.630 --> 00:35.440
I had not sufficient light for my employment and I remained idle in a pause of consideration

00:35.440 --> 00:40.260
of whether I should leave my labour for the night or hasten its conclusion by an unremitting

00:40.260 --> 00:41.360
attention to it.

00:41.940 --> 00:47.760
As I sat, a train of reflection occurred to me which led me to consider the effects of

00:47.760 --> 00:49.080
what I was now doing.

00:49.660 --> 00:55.620
Three years before I was engaged in the same manner and had created a fiend whose unparalleled

00:55.620 --> 01:00.780
barbarity had desolated my heart and filled it forever with the bitterest remorse.

01:01.740 --> 01:07.360
I was now about to form another being of whose dispositions I was alike ignorant.

01:07.800 --> 01:13.280
She might become ten thousand times more malignant than her mate and delight for its own sake

01:13.280 --> 01:15.460
in murder and wretchedness.

01:16.120 --> 01:21.360
He had sworn to quit the neighbourhood of man and hide himself in deserts, but she had

01:22.040 --> 01:28.060
And she, who in all probability was to become a thinking and reasoning animal, might refuse

01:28.060 --> 01:30.720
to comply with a compact made before her creation.

01:31.220 --> 01:36.860
They might even hate each other, the creature who already lived loathed his own deformity,

01:37.240 --> 01:42.040
and might he not conceive a greater abhorrence for it when it came before his eyes in the

01:42.040 --> 01:42.920
female form?

01:43.640 --> 01:48.260
She might also turn with disgust from him to the superior beauty of man.

01:48.260 --> 01:54.840
She might quit him, and he, being again alone, exasperated by the fresh provocation of being

01:54.840 --> 01:57.100
deserted by one of his own species.

01:58.140 --> 02:03.160
Even if they were to leave Europe and inhabit the deserts of the New World, yet one of the

02:03.160 --> 02:08.620
results of those sympathies for which the demon thirsted would be children, and a race

02:08.620 --> 02:14.100
of devils would be propagated upon the earth who might make the very existence of the species

02:14.100 --> 02:17.460
of man a condition precarious and full of terror.

02:17.960 --> 02:23.660
Had I right, for my own benefit, to inflict this curse upon everlasting generations?

02:24.580 --> 02:28.700
I had been moved by the sophisms of the being I had created.

02:29.620 --> 02:35.420
I had been struck senseless by his fiendish threats, but now, for the first time, the

02:35.420 --> 02:37.860
wickedness of my promise burst upon me.

02:38.720 --> 02:43.660
I shuddered to think that future ages might curse me as their pest, whose selfishness

02:43.660 --> 02:49.280
had not hesitated to buy its own piece at the price, perhaps, of the existence of the

02:49.280 --> 02:50.760
whole human race.

02:51.700 --> 02:59.420
I trembled, and my heart felled within me when, on looking up, I saw by the light of

02:59.420 --> 03:01.680
the moon the demon at the casement.

03:02.500 --> 03:08.240
A ghastly grin wrinkled his lips as he gazed on me, where I sat fulfilling the task which

03:08.240 --> 03:09.860
he had allotted to me.

03:09.860 --> 03:16.900
Yes, he had followed me in my travels, he had loitered in forests, hid himself in caves,

03:17.280 --> 03:24.000
or taken refuge in wide and desert heaths, and now he came to mark my progress and claim

03:24.000 --> 03:25.880
the fulfilment of my promise.

03:26.780 --> 03:33.620
As I looked on him, his countenance expressed the utmost extent of malice and treachery.

03:33.620 --> 03:39.540
I thought with a sensation of madness on my promise of creating another like to him,

03:40.280 --> 03:45.040
and trembling with passion, tore to pieces the thing on which I was engaged.

03:45.680 --> 03:51.360
The wretch saw me destroy the creature, on whose future existence he depended for happiness,

03:51.960 --> 03:56.460
and with a howl of devilish despair and revenge, withdrew.

03:57.260 --> 04:03.700
I left the room and, locking the door, made a solemn vow in my own heart never to resume

04:03.700 --> 04:09.380
my labours, and then, with trembling steps, I sought my own apartment.

04:10.000 --> 04:15.540
I was alone, none were near me to dissipate the gloom and relieve me from the sickening

04:15.540 --> 04:18.340
oppression of the most terrible reveries.

04:19.360 --> 04:24.420
Several hours passed, and I remained near my window gazing on the sea.

04:24.420 --> 04:30.480
It was almost motionless, for the winds were hushed, and all nature opposed under the eye

04:30.480 --> 04:31.540
of the quiet moon.

04:32.260 --> 04:37.900
A few fishing vessels alone specked the water, and now and then the gentle breeze wafted

04:37.900 --> 04:41.040
the sound of voices as the fishermen called to one another.

04:42.000 --> 04:47.680
I felt the silence, although I was hardly conscious of its extreme profundity, until

04:47.680 --> 04:53.000
my ear was suddenly arrested by the paddling of oars near the shore, and a person landed

04:53.000 --> 04:54.400
close to my house.

04:55.880 --> 05:01.500
In a few minutes after, I heard the creaking of my door, as if someone endeavoured to open

05:01.500 --> 05:02.180
it softly.

05:02.900 --> 05:09.040
I trembled from head to foot, I felt a presentiment of who it was, and wished to where I was one

05:09.040 --> 05:14.840
of the peasants who dwelt in a cottage not far from mine, but I was overcome by the sensation

05:14.840 --> 05:20.800
of helplessness, so often felt in frightful dreams, when you in vain endeavoured to fly

05:20.800 --> 05:24.160
from an impending danger and was routed to the spot.

05:25.020 --> 05:31.080
Presently I heard the sound of footsteps along the passage, the door opened, and the

05:31.080 --> 05:34.460
wretch, whom I dreaded, appeared.

05:35.940 --> 05:40.540
Shutting the door, he approached me and said in a smothered voice,

05:41.340 --> 05:44.600
You have destroyed the work which you began.

05:45.220 --> 05:46.640
Was it that you intend?

05:47.660 --> 05:49.540
Do you dare to break your promise?

05:50.150 --> 05:52.780
I have endured toil and misery.

05:53.280 --> 05:55.140
I left Switzerland with you.

05:55.400 --> 06:00.680
I crept along the shores of the Rhine, among its willow islands, and over the summits of

06:00.680 --> 06:01.360
its hills.

06:01.900 --> 06:07.080
I have dwelt many months in the heaths of England, and among the deserts of Scotland.

06:07.620 --> 06:11.740
I have endured incalculable fatigue and cold, and hunger.

06:12.380 --> 06:14.400
Do you dare destroy my hopes?

06:15.900 --> 06:16.560
Be gone!

06:17.040 --> 06:18.760
I do break my promise.

06:18.760 --> 06:25.120
Never will I create another like yourself, equal in deformity and wickedness.

06:26.100 --> 06:33.100
Slave, I before reasoned with you, but you have proved yourself unworthy of my condescension.

06:34.080 --> 06:36.380
Remember that I have power.

06:37.040 --> 06:44.520
You believe yourself miserable, but I can make you so wretched that the light of day

06:44.520 --> 06:46.200
will be hateful to you.

06:46.940 --> 06:51.220
You are my creator, but I am your master.

06:51.760 --> 06:52.340
Obey!

06:54.220 --> 07:00.320
The hour of my irresolution is past, and the period of your power is arrived.

07:00.960 --> 07:07.400
Your threats cannot move me to do an act of wickedness, but they confirm in me a determination

07:07.400 --> 07:10.720
of not creating you a companion in vice.

07:11.160 --> 07:18.420
Shall I, in cold blood, set loose upon the earth a demon whose delight is in death and

07:18.420 --> 07:19.240
wretchedness?

07:19.860 --> 07:20.420
Be gone!

07:21.000 --> 07:25.620
I am firm, and your words only exasperate my rage.

07:27.180 --> 07:33.100
The monster saw my determination in my face, and gnashed his teeth in the impotence of

07:33.100 --> 07:33.540
anger.

07:34.260 --> 07:43.380
Shall each man, cried he, find a wife for his bosom, and each beast have his mate, and

07:43.380 --> 07:44.560
I be alone?

07:45.200 --> 07:51.540
I had feelings of affection, and they were requited by detestation and scorn.

07:52.140 --> 07:55.360
Man, you may hate, but beware!

07:55.980 --> 08:02.440
Your hours will pass in dread and misery, and soon the bolt will fall which must ravage

08:02.440 --> 08:04.320
you from your happiness forever.

08:05.360 --> 08:06.740
Are you to be happy?

08:07.020 --> 08:10.220
Will I grovel in the intensity of my wretchedness?

08:10.880 --> 08:18.640
You can blast my other passions, but revenge remains, revenge henceforth dearer than light

08:18.640 --> 08:19.520
or food.

08:20.240 --> 08:29.800
I may die, but first you, my tyrant and tormentor, shall curse the sun that gazes on your misery.

08:31.020 --> 08:35.340
Beware, for I am fearless, and therefore powerful.

08:36.080 --> 08:41.020
I will watch with the wiliness of a snake, that I may sting with its venom.

08:42.000 --> 08:46.440
Man, you shall repent of the injuries you inflict.

08:48.660 --> 08:54.100
Devil, cease, and do not poison the air with these sounds of malice.

08:54.100 --> 09:00.020
I have declared my resolution to you, and I am no coward to bend beneath words.

09:00.720 --> 09:03.280
Leave me, I am inexorable.

09:05.080 --> 09:13.640
It is well, I go, but remember, I shall be with you on your wedding night.

09:14.740 --> 09:17.720
I started forward and exclaimed,

09:18.400 --> 09:25.120
Villain, before you sign my death warrant, be sure that you yourself safe.

09:26.520 --> 09:32.400
I would have seized him, but he eluded me and quitted the house with precipitation.

09:33.540 --> 09:40.360
In a few moments I saw him in his boat, which shot across the waters with an arrow-y swiftness,

09:40.760 --> 09:43.040
and was soon lost amidst the waves.

09:43.920 --> 09:49.420
All was again silent, but his words rang in my ears.

09:50.340 --> 09:56.080
I burned with rage to pursue the murderer of my peace and precipitate him into the ocean.

09:57.120 --> 10:00.760
I walked up and down my room hastily and perturbed,

10:01.000 --> 10:06.200
while my imagination conjured up a thousand images to torment and sting me.

10:06.960 --> 10:11.140
Why had I not followed him and closed with him in mortal strife?

10:11.880 --> 10:17.680
But I had suffered him to depart, and he had directed his course towards the mainland.

10:19.940 --> 10:25.760
I shuddered to think who might be the next victim sacrificed to his insatiable revenge.

10:26.980 --> 10:29.440
And then I thought again of his words,

10:30.500 --> 10:33.660
I will be with you on your wedding night.

10:34.600 --> 10:39.560
That, then, was the period fixed for the fulfilment of my destiny.

10:40.340 --> 10:46.080
In that hour I should die and at once satisfy and extinguish his malice.

10:46.880 --> 10:52.780
The prospect did not move me to fear, yet when I thought of my beloved Elizabeth,

10:53.320 --> 11:00.120
of her tears and endless sorrow, when she should find her lover so barbariously snatched from her,

11:00.560 --> 11:06.440
tears, the first I had shed for many months, streamed from my eyes,

11:06.440 --> 11:11.020
and I resolved not to fall before my enemy without a bitter struggle.

11:14.840 --> 11:18.700
The night passed away, and the sun rose from the ocean.

11:19.420 --> 11:23.580
My feelings became calmer, if it may be called calmness,

11:23.640 --> 11:27.300
when the violence of rage sinks into the depths of despair.

11:28.180 --> 11:32.320
I left the house, the horrid scene of last night's contention,

11:32.320 --> 11:37.140
and walked on the beach of the sea, which I almost regarded as an

11:37.140 --> 11:40.540
insurmountable barrier between me and my fellow creatures.

11:41.000 --> 11:46.760
Nay, a wish that such should prove the fact stole across me.

11:47.640 --> 11:51.460
I desired that I might pass my life on that barren rock.

11:52.080 --> 11:57.420
Wearily, it is true, but uninterrupted by any sudden shock of misery.

11:58.220 --> 12:04.580
If I returned, it was to be sacrificed, or to see those whom I loved most

12:04.580 --> 12:09.040
die under the grasp of a demon whom I had myself created.

12:10.660 --> 12:13.420
I walked about the isle like a restless spectre,

12:14.380 --> 12:17.900
separated from all it loved and miserable in the separation.

12:18.860 --> 12:21.680
When it became noon and the sun rose higher,

12:22.320 --> 12:26.160
I lay down on the grass and was overpowered by a deep sleep.

12:27.420 --> 12:32.300
I had been awake the whole of the preceding night, my nerves were agitated,

12:32.940 --> 12:35.960
and my eyes inflamed by watching and misery.

12:37.080 --> 12:41.740
The sleep into which I now sank refreshed me, and when I awoke,

12:42.260 --> 12:46.740
I again felt as if I belonged to a race of human beings like myself,

12:47.300 --> 12:51.860
and I began to reflect upon what had passed with greater composure.

12:52.780 --> 12:58.320
Yet still, the words of the fiend rang in my ears like a death knell.

12:58.560 --> 13:04.080
They appeared like a dream, yet distinct and oppressive as a reality.

13:05.220 --> 13:09.680
The sun had far descended, and I sat still on the shore,

13:10.200 --> 13:15.120
satisfying my appetite, which had become ravenous, with an oaten cake.

13:15.660 --> 13:20.820
When I saw a fishing boat land close to me, and one of the men brought me a packet,

13:21.420 --> 13:26.540
it contained letters from Geneva and one from Clearville entreating me to join him.

13:26.720 --> 13:31.280
He said that he was wearing away his time fruitlessly where he was,

13:31.660 --> 13:35.960
that the letters from the friends he had formed in London desired his return

13:35.960 --> 13:40.920
to complete the negotiation they had entered into for his Indian enterprise.

13:41.680 --> 13:47.560
I could no longer delay his departure, but as his journey to London might be followed,

13:47.560 --> 13:52.260
even sooner than he now conjectured, by his longer voyage,

13:52.680 --> 13:57.380
he entreated me to bestow as much of my society on him as I could spare.

13:58.460 --> 14:03.920
He besought me, therefore, to leave my solitary isle and to meet him at Perth,

14:04.080 --> 14:06.240
that we might proceed southwards together.

14:07.240 --> 14:10.080
This letter in a degree recalled me to life,

14:10.460 --> 14:14.540
and I determined to quit my island at the expiration of two days.

14:15.420 --> 14:21.520
Yet before I departed, there was a task to perform, on which I shuddered to reflect.

14:22.300 --> 14:29.620
I must pack up my chemical instruments, and for that purpose, I must enter the room which had been

14:29.620 --> 14:37.340
the scene of my odious work, and I must handle those utensils, the sight of which was sickening

14:37.340 --> 14:44.960
me. The next morning, at daybreak, I summoned sufficient courage and unlocked the door of my

14:44.960 --> 14:52.760
laboratory. The remains of the half-finished creature, whom I had destroyed, laid scattered

14:52.760 --> 14:59.140
on the floor, and I almost felt as if I had mingled with the living flesh of a human being.

14:59.660 --> 15:03.660
I paused to collect myself, and then entered the chamber.

15:04.500 --> 15:11.560
With trembling hand, I conveyed the instruments out of the room, but I reflected that I ought

15:11.560 --> 15:16.720
not to leave the relics of my work to excite the horror and suspicion of the peasants,

15:17.060 --> 15:23.780
and I accordingly put them into a basket with a great quantity of stones, and laying them up,

15:23.780 --> 15:30.100
determined to throw them into the sea that very night. And in the meantime, I sat upon the beach,

15:30.100 --> 15:33.940
employed in cleaning and arranging my chemical apparatus.

15:35.860 --> 15:41.480
Nothing could be more complete than the alteration that had taken place in my feelings since the night

15:41.480 --> 15:48.620
of the appearance of the demon. I had before regarded my promise with gloomy despair as a

15:48.620 --> 15:56.040
thing that, with whatever consequences, must be fulfilled. But now I felt as if a film had been

15:56.040 --> 16:04.240
from before my eyes, and that I saw for the first time clearly. The idea of renewing my labors

16:04.240 --> 16:11.960
did not for one instant occur to me, the threat I had weighed upon my thoughts, but I did not reflect

16:11.960 --> 16:19.420
that a voluntary act of mine could avert it. I had resolved in my own mind that to create another

16:19.420 --> 16:25.680
like the fiend I had first made would be an act of the basest and most atrocious selfishness

16:25.680 --> 16:31.320
and I banished from my mind every thought that could lead to a different conclusion.

16:32.720 --> 16:38.980
Between two and three in the morning the moon rose, and I then, putting my basket aboard a little

16:38.980 --> 16:47.340
skiff, sailed out about four miles from the shore. The scene was perfectly solitary, a few boats were

16:47.340 --> 16:54.240
returning towards land, but I sailed away from them. I felt as if I was about the commission of

16:54.240 --> 17:00.300
dreadful crime and avoided with shuddering anxiety any encounter with my fellow creatures.

17:01.480 --> 17:08.180
At one time the moon, which had been before clear, was suddenly overspread by a thick cloud,

17:08.760 --> 17:15.280
and I took advantage of the moment of darkness and cast my basket into the sea. I listened to

17:15.280 --> 17:22.580
the gurgling sound as it sank and then sailed away from the spot. The sky became clouded,

17:22.580 --> 17:27.640
but the air was pure, although chilled by the northeast breeze that was then rising.

17:28.960 --> 17:34.740
But it refreshed me and filled me with such agreeable sensations that I resolved to prolong

17:34.740 --> 17:40.940
my stay on the water, and fixing the rudder in a direct position, stretched myself at the bottom

17:40.940 --> 17:49.000
of the boat. Clouds hid the moon, everything was obscure, and I heard only the sound of the boat as

17:49.000 --> 17:56.020
keel cut through the waves. The murmur lulled me, and in a short time I slept soundly.

17:56.920 --> 18:03.100
I do not know how long I remained in this situation, but when I awoke I found that the

18:03.100 --> 18:10.260
sun had already mounted considerably. The wind was high and the waves continually threatened the

18:10.260 --> 18:17.220
safety of my little skiff. I found the wind was northeast and must have driven me far from the

18:17.220 --> 18:23.280
coast from which I had embarked. I endeavored to change my course, but quickly found that if I

18:23.280 --> 18:29.640
again made the attempt the abode would instantly be filled with water. Thus situated, my only

18:29.640 --> 18:37.360
resource was to drive before the wind. I confess that I felt a few sensations of terror. I had no

18:37.360 --> 18:42.800
compass with me, and was so slenderly acquainted with the geography of this part of the world

18:42.800 --> 18:48.500
that the sun was of little benefit to me. I might be driven into the wild Atlantic

18:48.500 --> 18:54.620
and feel all the torches of starvation, or be swallowed up in the immeasurable waters that

18:54.620 --> 19:01.220
roared and buffeted around me. I had already been out many hours and felt the torment of a burning

19:01.220 --> 19:08.340
thirst, a prelude to my other sufferings. I looked upon the heavens which were covered by clouds that

19:08.340 --> 19:17.060
flew before the wind, only to be replaced by others. I looked upon the sea. It was to be my grave.

19:18.300 --> 19:27.200
Fiend! I exclaimed. Your task is already fulfilled. I thought of Elizabeth, of my father,

19:27.640 --> 19:34.340
and of Clairvaux, all left behind, on whom the monster might satisfy his sanctuary

19:34.340 --> 19:41.920
and merciless passions. This idea plunged me into a reverie so despairing and frightful

19:41.920 --> 19:49.120
that even now, when the scene is on the point of closing before me forever, I shudder to reflect on

19:49.120 --> 19:57.520
it. Some hours passed thus, but by degrees, as the sun declined towards the horizon,

19:57.520 --> 20:02.960
the wind died away into a gentle breeze and the sea became free from breakers.

20:04.000 --> 20:09.700
But these gave place to a heavy swell. I felt sick and hardly able to hold the rudder,

20:09.840 --> 20:16.760
when suddenly I saw a line of high land towards the south. Almost spent as I was,

20:17.100 --> 20:23.500
by fatigue and the dreadful suspense I had endured for several hours, this sudden certainty of life

20:23.500 --> 20:30.580
rushed like a flood of warm joy to my heart and tears gushed from my eyes. How mutable are our

20:30.580 --> 20:37.020
feelings and how strange it is that the clinging love we have of life, even in the excess of

20:37.020 --> 20:44.120
misery! I constructed another sail with a part of my dress and eagerly steered my course towards

20:44.120 --> 20:50.880
the land. It had a wild and rocky appearance, but as I approached nearer, I easily perceived

20:50.880 --> 20:57.880
traces of cultivation. I saw vessels near the shore and found myself suddenly transported

20:57.880 --> 21:04.180
back to the neighbourhood of civilised man. I carefully traced the windings of the land

21:04.180 --> 21:09.620
and hailed a steeple at which I at length saw issuing from behind a small promontory.

21:10.540 --> 21:17.380
As I was in a state of extreme debility, I resolved to sail towards the town as a place

21:17.380 --> 21:23.060
where I could most easily procure nourishment. Fortunately, I had money with me.

21:24.240 --> 21:30.880
As I turned the promontory, I perceived a small neat town and a good harbour which I entered,

21:31.340 --> 21:38.000
my heart bounding with joy at my unexpected escape. As I was occupied in fixing the boat

21:38.000 --> 21:44.580
and arranging the sails, several people crowded towards the spot. They seemed much surprised at

21:44.580 --> 21:51.460
my appearance, but instead of offering me any assistance, whispered together with gestures that

21:51.460 --> 21:56.680
at any other time might have produced in me a slight sensation of alarm.

21:57.500 --> 22:03.320
As it was, I merely remarked that they spoke English and I therefore addressed them in that

22:03.320 --> 22:10.680
language. My good friends, said I, will you be so kind as to tell me the name of this town

22:10.680 --> 22:18.140
and inform me where I am? You will know that soon enough, replied a man with a hoarse voice.

22:18.840 --> 22:22.780
Maybe you come to a place that will not prove much to your taste,

22:23.280 --> 22:27.320
but you will not be consulted as to your quarters, I promise you.

22:28.420 --> 22:34.900
I was exceedingly surprised on receiving so rude an answer from a stranger, and I was also

22:34.900 --> 22:40.020
disconcerted on the perceiving the frowning and angry countenances of his companions.

22:41.000 --> 22:47.500
Why do you answer me so roughly? I replied, surely it is not the custom of Englishmen to

22:47.500 --> 22:56.620
receive strangers so inhospitably. I do not know, said the man, what the custom of the English may be,

22:57.080 --> 23:03.820
but it is the custom of the Irish to hate villains. While this strange dialogue continued,

23:03.820 --> 23:11.320
I perceived the crowd rapidly increase. Their faces expressed a mixture of curiosity and anger,

23:12.000 --> 23:19.960
which annoyed and in some degree alarmed me. I inquired the way to the inn, but no one replied.

23:20.920 --> 23:27.660
I then moved forward and a murmuring sound arose from the crowd as they followed and surrounded me

23:27.660 --> 23:32.040
when an ill-looking man approaching tapped me on the shoulder and said,

23:32.600 --> 23:37.900
Come, sir, you must follow me to Mr. Kerwin's to give an account of yourself.

23:39.780 --> 23:46.080
Who is Mr. Kerwin? Why am I to give an account of myself? Is this not a free country?

23:47.440 --> 23:53.000
Aye, sir, free enough for honest folks. Mr. Kerwin is a magistrate,

23:53.420 --> 23:58.220
and you are to give an account of the death of a gentleman who was found murdered here last night.

23:59.340 --> 24:07.780
This answer startled me, but I presently recovered myself. I was innocent. That could easily be

24:07.780 --> 24:14.020
proved. Accordingly, I followed my conductor in silence and was led to one of the best houses in

24:14.020 --> 24:21.240
the town. I was ready to sink from fatigue and hunger, but being surrounded by a crowd,

24:21.820 --> 24:27.820
I thought it politic to rouse all my strength so that no physical debility might be construed into

24:27.820 --> 24:35.760
apprehension or conscious guilt. Little did I then expect the calamity that was in a few moments to

24:35.760 --> 24:44.800
overwhelm me and extinguish in horror and despair all fear of ignominy or death. I might pause here,

24:45.160 --> 24:51.320
for it requires all my fortitude to recall the memory of the frightful events which I am about

24:51.320 --> 24:55.160
to relate in proper detail to my recollection.

